"""
MKT Context Commentary — Job chapters 19–21
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-job-19-21.py

Ch 19: Job's response to Bildad — the famous gō'ēl (Redeemer) passage; military siege
    imagery for divine abandonment; monumental inscription wish; ANE social honor-shame
    and the complete dissolution of relational networks; the legal institution of the
    kinsman-redeemer and its implications for resurrection hope.
Ch 20: Zophar's retribution theology — the poison metaphor (cobra venom / rō'sh);
    heaven and earth as legal witnesses (treaty-witness formula); divine warrior weapons
    in Mesopotamian and Ugaritic texts; the greed-reversal motif in ANE wisdom.
Ch 21: Job's theodicy inversion — direct challenge to retribution doctrine; the
    prosperity of the wicked as empirical counterevidence; the cup of wrath; death
    as equalizer (Eccl 9:2 parallel); the appeal to travelers as universal witnesses.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "19": {
    "1": "<p>The standard speech-attribution formula (&ldquo;Then Job answered and said&rdquo;) marks the third cycle of dialogues. By this point in the book, this formula has appeared over a dozen times; its repetition is a formal literary device that organizes the dialogue into discrete speeches. In ANE wisdom literature, the attribution formula also functions to assign authorial responsibility for the argument that follows &mdash; each speaker owns their claims before the divine council that is implicitly present throughout the book.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The verb <em>dākhā&rsquo;</em> (to crush, pulverize) describes physical violence applied to a person's soul. The word is the same root used of the crushed Servant in Isa 53:5,10 (<em>medukhkā&rsquo;</em>). In the honor-shame culture of the ancient Near East, verbal abuse that exposed a person's disgrace before witnesses carried the social force of physical violence &mdash; it destroyed standing and identity. Job&rsquo;s accusation that the friends are crushing his spirit with words reflects this understanding.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;Ten times now you have reproached me&rdquo; is an idiomatic expression meaning &ldquo;many times&rdquo; rather than a precise count &mdash; the same idiom appears in Gen 31:7,41 where Laban changed Jacob&rsquo;s wages &ldquo;ten times.&rdquo; In ANE social ethics, the obligation to support a suffering friend was widely recognized; the Babylonian wisdom text <em>Counsels of Wisdom</em> advises a man not to shame a supplicant. The friends&rsquo; repeated reproaches represent a social failure recognized as such by the ANE moral tradition they claim to represent.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Job&rsquo;s conditional argument &mdash; &ldquo;even if I erred, the error is with me alone&rdquo; &mdash; reflects the ANE legal distinction between public and private liability. In ancient Near Eastern law codes (Hammurabi, Middle Assyrian Laws), crimes were classified by whether they affected communal order (requiring public adjudication) or only the individual. Job claims his alleged error is a private matter between himself and God, not a communal disgrace that justifies the friends&rsquo; public shaming campaign.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The verb &ldquo;magnify yourselves against me&rdquo; is the language of honor-contest in ANE culture. In a shame culture, one person&rsquo;s social rise necessarily involved another&rsquo;s fall &mdash; honor was a limited good. The friends&rsquo; act of pressing Job&rsquo;s disgrace as evidence is, in this social framework, simultaneously a claim about Job&rsquo;s guilt and a bid for their own superior status. This social dynamic is one reason Job&rsquo;s vindication at the end (42:7&ndash;9) must be public and formal.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Job&rsquo;s claim that God has &ldquo;overthrown me&rdquo; (<em>&rsquo;iwwetanî</em>, perverted/bent my case) uses a legal term for judicial corruption: a judge who perverts justice (Deut 16:19, &ldquo;you must not pervert justice&rdquo;). This is Job&rsquo;s most theologically audacious charge &mdash; he accuses God of acting as a corrupt judge. The &ldquo;net&rdquo; (<em>mᵉṣûdātô</em>) around him evokes the divine-warrior&rsquo;s net used to capture enemies in Mesopotamian iconography (e.g., the Stele of the Vultures, ca. 2450 BCE, shows a divine net holding captive enemies).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The cry of <em>ḥāmās</em> (&ldquo;Violence!&rdquo;) is the formal appeal of a crime victim in ancient Israelite legal procedure &mdash; the cry that triggers communal obligation to respond and adjudicate (cf. Gen 6:11 where the earth is filled with <em>ḥāmās</em>; Hab 1:2 where Habakkuk cries <em>ḥāmās</em> to God without answer). Job&rsquo;s lament that there is &ldquo;no verdict&rdquo; (<em>mišpāṭ</em>) describes a total breakdown of the justice system: the crime victim&rsquo;s formal cry goes unanswered, and no court delivers a ruling.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The &ldquo;walled road&rdquo; and &ldquo;darkness over my paths&rdquo; invert 1:10 where the same vocabulary of a protective fence described God&rsquo;s blessing. The adversary had complained that God had built a hedge (<em>śûkāh</em>) of protection around Job; now God has walled Job in with an impassable wall (<em>gādar</em>). The same divine action &mdash; surrounding Job &mdash; now functions as imprisonment rather than protection. Ancient Israelite thought recognized this paradox: the God who protects and the God who restricts use the same sovereign power.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Stripping Job of &ldquo;honor&rdquo; (<em>kābôd</em>) and &ldquo;crown&rdquo; (<em>&rsquo;ăṭāret rō&rsquo;š</em>) describes the dismantling of ANE social identity through public symbols. The crown or wreath was a visible marker of status throughout the ancient Near East &mdash; royal crowns, priestly headgear, and civic wreaths all marked the wearer&rsquo;s standing. Job&rsquo;s honor was established in ch29:7&ndash;25 (elders standing when he entered, princes silenced, the nobility listening attentively); the stripping of this honor is the social equivalent of public execution.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The uprooting of hope &ldquo;like a tree&rdquo; is a common ANE metaphor for the destruction of flourishing. Mesopotamian royal inscriptions frequently describe defeated enemies as trees torn out by the roots. The tree as a symbol of prosperity, hope, and established life appears throughout OT wisdom (Ps 1:3; 92:12&ndash;14; Jer 17:8). A uprooted tree cannot be replanted &mdash; unlike cut trees that can regenerate from stumps (Job 14:7 uses this imagery), Job describes uprooting as total and irreversible destruction.</p>",
    "11": "<p>God counting Job &ldquo;as one of his enemies&rdquo; reverses the friend relationship implied by divine favor. In ANE treaty and covenant language, the parties are defined as friends or enemies: the covenant formula &ldquo;your enemies are my enemies&rdquo; established the friend-of-friend / enemy-of-enemy solidarity network. By counting Job as an enemy, God has in effect annulled the covenant relationship. This is why Job repeatedly demands a hearing rather than simply submitting &mdash; he is appealing to the covenant bond that he believes should make God his legal defender, not his adversary.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The military siege imagery &mdash; troops advancing together, heaping up siege ramps, encamping around the tent &mdash; reflects the standard tactics of Bronze Age and Iron Age siege warfare as attested in Assyrian reliefs and military annals. The siege ramp (<em>sōlelāh</em>) was a characteristic Assyrian technique: engineers built earthen ramps against city walls to allow assault troops to attack at wall-height. The imagery of a divine army besieging a single human&rsquo;s tent is deliberately grotesque in its disproportion, evoking the cosmic absurdity of Job&rsquo;s situation.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The systematic severing of relational networks in vv13&ndash;19 proceeds from the most distant to the most intimate, then to the most contemptible. <strong>Brothers</strong> (<em>&rsquo;aḥay</em>) and <strong>acquaintances</strong> (<em>yōdᵉ&rsquo;ay</em>) failing first is a social statement: in ANE clan culture, blood-brothers were the primary support network after God himself (cf. Prov 17:17). Their estrangement means the first ring of protection has collapsed. The word &ldquo;wholly estranged&rdquo; (<em>yizzārû</em>) has the sense of becoming foreigners &mdash; the precise opposite of the covenant solidarity that kin-relationships required.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;Familiar friends&rdquo; (<em>mᵉyudda&rsquo;ay</em>, known ones) represents the second circle of social support &mdash; beyond blood-kin, the network of trusted associates built through covenant of salt, guest-friendship, and long acquaintance. In ancient Near Eastern social structures, these relationships were maintained by hospitality and mutual aid obligations. The failure of <em>mᵉyudda&rsquo;ay</em> describes the breakdown of the voluntary social network that supplemented the mandatory obligations of kinship.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Household members (<em>gārê bêtî</em>, sojourners of my house) treating Job as a stranger inverts the household economy of the ancient Levant. The <em>paterfamilias</em> was the legal and social center of the household; his word was law and his presence defined the household&rsquo;s identity. The term &ldquo;foreigner&rdquo; (<em>nokrî</em>) was the strongest social category of outside-ness: one who has no claims on the household&rsquo;s hospitality or protection. To be called a foreigner in one&rsquo;s own house is the complete inversion of patriarchal identity.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The reversal of the master-servant relationship in Job&rsquo;s household reflects the total collapse of his social authority. In ancient Near Eastern household law, a servant who failed to respond to his master&rsquo;s call could be punished severely; the servant&rsquo;s silence is a statement of the complete erosion of Job&rsquo;s authority. The detail that Job had to &ldquo;beg him with his own mouth&rdquo; describes the humiliation of a master reduced to the posture of a supplicant &mdash; the social inversion is total and the shame is public within the household hierarchy.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The repulsiveness of Job&rsquo;s breath to his wife reflects both the physical reality of severe illness and its social consequences. Skin diseases in the ancient Near East created social exclusion beyond the visible condition &mdash; odor, discharge, and physical repulsiveness activated the purity codes that separated the sick from the community. The phrase &ldquo;sons of my own body&rdquo; is unusual; the traditional reading (&ldquo;sons of my mother&rsquo;s womb,&rdquo; i.e., full brothers) creates a parallel with the wife, intensifying the social rejection: even the closest of kin recoil.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Young children despising a suffering elder represents the complete inversion of ANE intergenerational respect. Wisdom literature uniformly mandated honor to elders as the fundamental social ethic (Lev 19:32; Prov 16:31; 20:29). In Elihu&rsquo;s speech (ch32), he is initially silent because of his youth, exemplifying the expected deference. The mockery of Job by children &mdash; not merely youth but specifically small children (<em>yᵉlādîm</em>) &mdash; represents the deepest possible social humiliation: he has lost even the dignity that the weakest and most unformed members of society owe to elders.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;Closest companions&rdquo; (<em>rāzay</em>, from <em>sōd</em>, council or intimate circle) were those admitted to one&rsquo;s private counsel. In ancient court culture, access to the king&rsquo;s private council was the highest mark of trust; wisdom literature regarded the <em>sōd YHWH</em> (the intimate council of God) as the place of prophetic revelation (Jer 23:18; Amos 3:7). The dissolution of Job&rsquo;s personal <em>sōd</em> &mdash; those he loved and trusted most &mdash; is the innermost ring of social abandonment after the outer rings have already collapsed.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;My bones cling to my skin and flesh&rdquo; describes extreme emaciation from illness. Ancient medical texts understood the relationship between fat, flesh, and bone as indicators of health; wasting diseases that left &ldquo;only bones&rdquo; were well-recognized clinical pictures in Mesopotamian medical literature (<em>Sakikku</em>). The phrase &ldquo;skin of my teeth&rdquo; (<em>bᵉ&rsquo;ôr šinnāy</em>) is a hapax idiom unique to this verse; teeth have no skin, so the phrase likely means &ldquo;by the narrowest margin&rdquo; or &ldquo;by my bare gums&rdquo; &mdash; a sardonic expression of having nothing left.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The double appeal &ldquo;have pity on me, have pity on me&rdquo; (<em>ḥonnûnî ḥonnûnî</em>) is a formal rhetorical intensification known as <em>anadiplosis</em>, used in Hebrew lament poetry for emphasis (cf. Ps 22:1: &ldquo;My God, my God&rdquo;). In ANE petitionary contexts, the repeated appeal to pity signaled the petitioner&rsquo;s extremity and the gravity of the request. The phrase &ldquo;the hand of God has touched me&rdquo; uses <em>yād</em> (hand) as the instrument of divine power and emphasizes that Job&rsquo;s suffering is a direct divine act, not merely misfortune.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Job&rsquo;s accusation that the friends pursue him &ldquo;like God&rdquo; identifies the mimetic relationship between the friends&rsquo; theological arguments and God&rsquo;s apparent actions: they are using the same logic of retribution to justify their condemnation of Job that would justify God&rsquo;s punishment. In so doing, they have arrogated a divine role &mdash; acting as judges in a case where God is both the accused and the judge. The phrase &ldquo;not satisfied with my flesh&rdquo; uses the idiom of a predator's appetite and echoes the adversary&rsquo;s own challenge (2:5: &ldquo;strike his flesh and his bone&rdquo;).</p>",
    "23": "<p>The wish for a permanent written record reflects the monumental inscription culture of the ancient Near East. From Sumerian royal inscriptions (ca. 2500 BCE) through the great Assyrian and Babylonian annals, powerful rulers commissioned stone and clay monuments to preserve their deeds. Job&rsquo;s desire for his words to be written down connects his case to this tradition of durable record &mdash; he wants a record that will outlast the present social disapproval and testify to a future audience. The legal undertone is strong: a written deposition preserves testimony for appeal.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The writing technologies listed &mdash; iron stylus, lead, and rock &mdash; all represent durable inscription methods attested in the ancient world. Iron tools were used to cut inscriptions into stone faces; lead tablets (found at various Mediterranean and Near Eastern sites) were used for private records and contracts; rock-face inscriptions were the most permanent of all (cf. the Siloam Tunnel inscription, the Mesha Stele). The specification of these materials is not poetic ornament but a precise statement: Job wants the most durable record possible, one that cannot be erased by time or his enemies.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The <em>gō&rsquo;ēl</em> (Redeemer/Kinsman-Redeemer) was a specific legal institution in ancient Israel with three primary functions: (1) buying back sold family land (Lev 25:25; Jer 32); (2) marrying a dead brother&rsquo;s widow to continue his line (Deut 25:5&ndash;10; Ruth 3&ndash;4); (3) avenging a murdered kinsman (Num 35:12&ndash;28). In all three functions, the <em>gō&rsquo;ēl</em> acted on behalf of a vulnerable family member who could not act for themselves. Job&rsquo;s declaration that his <em>gō&rsquo;ēl</em> lives and will stand on the earth asserts that he has a legal advocate in the divine court who will ultimately act in his behalf.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The phrase &ldquo;after my skin is thus destroyed&rdquo; followed by &ldquo;yet from within my flesh I shall see God&rdquo; presents one of the most debated theological statements in the OT regarding bodily resurrection. The Septuagint and the Vulgate both read this as a resurrection hope. While Sheol in the OT is generally a place of silence where the dead do not praise God (Ps 88:10&ndash;12), resurrection language appears in Isa 26:19; Ezek 37; Dan 12:2; and Ps 16:10. Whether Job articulates resurrection hope or a transcendent vision before death, the verse moves beyond the usual OT horizon &mdash; a theological breakthrough within the extremity of suffering.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The thrice-repeated personal pronoun &mdash; &ldquo;I myself shall see him, my own eyes shall behold, not a stranger&rsquo;s eyes&rdquo; &mdash; is among the most emphatic statements of personal divine encounter in the OT. The language of &ldquo;seeing God&rdquo; (<em>ḥāzāh &rsquo;ĕlôah</em>) is the language of theophany and prophetic vision (cf. Isa 6:1; Ezek 1:1; Amos 9:1). What Job desires &mdash; and what the book delivers in ch38&ndash;41 &mdash; is not vindication through a third party but a direct encounter with the divine. The phrase &ldquo;my heart fails within me&rdquo; (<em>kāl&û kikkhyôtay</em>) expresses the consuming longing of this desire.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The rhetorical question Job anticipates from the friends &mdash; &ldquo;Why do we still pursue him?&rdquo; &mdash; is the legal language of a prosecution deciding whether to continue a case. Job predicts they will give up the pursuit only when they discover that &ldquo;the root of the matter is found in me&rdquo; &mdash; meaning either that the source of the trouble lies within Job (the friends&rsquo; view) or within them (Job&rsquo;s warning). The ambiguity is deliberate and fits the adversarial legal frame: the question of where the root of trouble lies is precisely what the divine court must adjudicate.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The final warning &mdash; &ldquo;fear the sword, for wrath brings the sword&rsquo;s punishment&rdquo; &mdash; turns the friends&rsquo; own retribution theology back against them. In ancient Israelite legal thought, false witnesses (<em>&rsquo;ēd šeqer</em>) were subject to the same punishment they sought to inflict (Deut 19:16&ndash;19: &ldquo;do to him as he schemed to do to his brother&rdquo;). Job warns that if they are lying about him, divine retribution will fall on them for their false testimony &mdash; precisely what YHWH&rsquo;s verdict in 42:7 confirms when God declares that the friends &ldquo;have not spoken of me what is right.&rdquo;</p>"
  },
  "20": {
    "1": "<p>The speech-attribution formula for Zophar the Naamathite &mdash; who has not spoken since ch11 &mdash; marks the resumption of his role in the third cycle of dialogue. Zophar represents the most rigid strand of wisdom theology in the book: his two speeches (chs 11 and 20) both end without sympathy for Job, and he will not speak in the third cycle at all. His geographic identity as a <em>Naamathite</em> (from Naamah, a location possibly in southern Canaan or north Arabia) places him in the tradition of non-Israelite wisdom, the &ldquo;East&rdquo; that Job himself represents.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Zophar&rsquo;s claim that he is compelled to answer by his &ldquo;urgency within&rdquo; reflects the ANE concept of wisdom as an uncontainable inner force. In Mesopotamian wisdom texts, the scribal sage was understood to possess a divine gift of insight (<em>nēmequ</em>) that had its own pressure toward expression. Elihu will make a similar claim in 32:18&ndash;19 (the spirit within him is like bottled wine; he must speak). The appeal to inner compulsion functions rhetorically to present Zophar&rsquo;s words as wisdom-inspiration rather than personal opinion, lending them the authority of a revealed tradition.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Zophar has received a &ldquo;reproof that dishonors me&rdquo; (<em>mûsar kᵉlimmātî</em>). In an honor culture, a public reproof by a social inferior was not merely unpleasant but was a formal challenge to the reproved person&rsquo;s social standing. The ANE ethic of public discourse required that one respond to such a challenge or implicitly concede the superior&rsquo;s point. Zophar&rsquo;s &ldquo;spirit from beyond my understanding&rdquo; that compels him is the same wisdom-spirit vocabulary Elihu uses; both claim that their response is not merely personal pride but divinely-mandated truth-speaking.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The appeal to primordial tradition &mdash; &ldquo;from of old, since man was set upon the earth&rdquo; &mdash; is a standard move in ancient wisdom rhetoric. In Mesopotamian wisdom, the appeal to antiquity validated a claim: what has always been true carries the weight of cosmic order. The <em>Babylonian Theodicy</em> (ca. 1000 BCE), a dialogue between a sufferer and a friend, opens with similar appeals to the established order of things. For Zophar, the retribution principle is not a recent theological opinion but a truth as old as human existence itself &mdash; encoded into the structure of the world.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;The triumph of the wicked is short, the joy of the godless lasts but a moment&rdquo; is the central theorem of Zophar&rsquo;s retribution theology, stated here as a universal axiom. This principle appears throughout OT wisdom (Ps 37:10&ndash;15; 73:18&ndash;20; Prov 10:25) and has its parallels in ANE texts. However, Job&rsquo;s counter-argument in ch21 will challenge this empirically: he will insist that the wicked frequently die in peace, grow old, and are honored in burial. The debate between Zophar and Job represents a genuine theological tension within the OT canon itself.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The image of the wicked man&rsquo;s greatness mounting &ldquo;to the heavens&rdquo; evokes the ancient Near Eastern motif of hubristic overreach into the divine sphere. The Tower of Babel (Gen 11:4) and the Babylonian king&rsquo;s self-deification speech (Isa 14:13&ndash;14: &ldquo;I will ascend to the heavens; I will raise my throne above the stars of God&rdquo;) use the same imagery. In ANE cosmology, the boundary between the human and divine spheres was absolute; crossing it was the definition of hubris and automatically invited divine retribution &mdash; a premise Zophar uses to strengthen his retribution argument.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The comparison &ldquo;he will perish forever like his own dung&rdquo; is one of the most viscerally contemptuous images in wisdom literature. In ANE social ethics, the contrast between the elevated person (head in the clouds, v6) and their ultimate degraded end was expressed in deliberately gross terms to emphasize the completeness of the reversal. The phrase &ldquo;those who saw him will say, Where is he?&rdquo; echoes the ancient lament formula for vanished greatness; in Mesopotamian royal laments, the fallen city or king is addressed with the same &ldquo;where is he/she?&rdquo; formula of bewildered loss.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;He flies away like a dream&rdquo; uses the ancient Near Eastern understanding of dreams as the most ephemeral form of existence &mdash; vivid and seemingly real during sleep, completely vanished upon waking. The dream-motif for impermanence appears in Ps 73:20 (&ldquo;like a dream when one awakes&rdquo;); ANE wisdom texts from Mesopotamia and Egypt also use the dream metaphor for fleeting prosperity. The parallel &ldquo;vision of the night&rdquo; (<em>ḥalyôn laylāh</em>) connects to the night-vision genre of prophetic literature (Dan 7; Zech 1) where the night vision was simultaneously authentic and ephem&shy;eral.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The personification of the wicked man&rsquo;s &ldquo;place&rdquo; (&ldquo;his own place will no longer recognize him&rdquo;) reflects the ancient understanding that people were ontologically bound to their land and household. In Mesopotamian thought, a person&rsquo;s <em>asrū</em> (place) was the physical locus of their identity and ancestral spirits. The concept of a place &ldquo;recognizing&rdquo; a person it once knew draws on the same personification. The claim that the wicked man&rsquo;s place rejects him expresses the cosmic totality of his erasure: even the ground disowns him.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The reversal motif &mdash; the wicked man&rsquo;s children seeking favor from the poor &mdash; inverts the normal hierarchy of the patron-client relationship that structured ANE society. The wealthy man held a network of clients who depended on his patronage; his children inheriting nothing is the complete collapse of this social structure. The Ugaritic <em>Tale of Aqhat</em> depicts the reversal of a noble household&rsquo;s fortune as one of the most devastating possible fates. The children&rsquo;s hands giving back ill-gotten wealth reflects the legal restitution obligation that fell on heirs for a deceased person&rsquo;s crimes.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;His bones are full of the sins of his youth&rdquo; reflects ANE medical-theological thinking about the relationship between sin and physical embodiment. Mesopotamian medical texts (particularly the <em>Sakikku</em> series on disease) attributed many conditions to sin embedded in the body; the phrasing suggests that youthful sins (<em>sins of his youth</em>) have literally saturated the skeletal structure. The idea that sin is &ldquo;stored up&rdquo; in the body until the day of reckoning is related to Eliphaz&rsquo;s claim in 15:35 and anticipates Paul&rsquo;s language about the &ldquo;body of sin&rdquo; (Rom 6:6).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The metaphor of evil as food that is &ldquo;sweet in his mouth&rdquo; and &ldquo;hidden under his tongue&rdquo; reflects the ancient gustatory metaphor for moral experience. Wisdom literature consistently uses taste as a moral register: wisdom itself is &ldquo;sweeter than honey&rdquo; (Ps 19:10; 119:103), and Job himself uses the taste metaphor in 6:7 for repulsive food. The hiding of evil &ldquo;under the tongue&rdquo; describes the behavior of savoring a pleasure while concealing it from others &mdash; a picture of deliberate, enjoyable wickedness rather than inadvertent sin.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The extended metaphor of holding evil in the mouth rather than swallowing or spitting it out develops the food imagery into a picture of moral addiction. In ancient wisdom texts, the self-indulgent person who cannot release a pleasure was regarded as enslaved to appetite &mdash; the opposite of the sage who exercises self-control. Proverbs uses similar food metaphors: &ldquo;the honey of the wicked is bitter in the end&rdquo; (cf. Prov 5:3&ndash;4). The deliberate delay (&ldquo;keeps it lodged&rdquo;) intensifies the picture of willful retention of what will ultimately poison.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The reversal of sweet-to-venom &mdash; &ldquo;his food turns in his stomach, becomes cobra venom inside him&rdquo; &mdash; draws on precise knowledge of Levantine serpent toxicology. The <em>pethen</em> (Naja haje, the Egyptian cobra) was among the most dangerous serpents known in the ancient Near East; its venom causes tissue destruction and systemic collapse. The image of ingested sweetness transforming into cobra venom in the digestive system is a physio-moral metaphor: the pleasure of sin, once swallowed, undergoes a chemical transformation into death-bringing poison.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The vomiting of swallowed wealth &mdash; expelled by God from the belly &mdash; connects to the ancient Near Eastern concept of divine reversal of unjust acquisition. In Mesopotamian legal thought, unjust wealth (gained through fraud, oppression, or false weights) was believed to carry a divine curse that would eventually expel it from the household. The &ldquo;God&rdquo; who acts here is grammatically the subject of the expulsion, making this an active divine reversal rather than merely natural consequence. Compare Jonah 2:10 where the fish &ldquo;vomited&rdquo; Jonah onto dry land &mdash; the same word used for divine expulsion of what should not be retained.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The escalation from cobra venom in the belly (v14) to drinking the venom of cobras and the viper&rsquo;s tongue is a rhetorical intensification that moves from internal digestion to external application. The <em>pethen</em> (cobra) and <em>eph&rsquo;eh</em> (viper, possibly the sand viper <em>Cerastes</em>) were the two most feared serpents in the ancient Levant. The image of the viper&rsquo;s tongue as lethal instrument reflects the ancient (pre-modern) belief that snakes injected venom through their tongues rather than their fangs &mdash; a zoological error that served the literary purpose of linking speech with poison (cf. Ps 58:4; 140:3).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The rivers of &ldquo;honey and curds&rdquo; that the wicked man will not look upon echo the ancient Near Eastern paradise-land motif. The land flowing with milk and honey (Exod 3:8,17; 13:5) is the paradigmatic image of divine blessing and provision in the OT. The Ugaritic paradise texts describe abundant moisture, rivers, and rich food as the characteristic of the blessed land. Zophar&rsquo;s point is that the wicked man will be excluded from the experience of divine abundance &mdash; the very covenant promise of the land that would normally mark divine favor.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The legal concept of forced restitution without consumption reflects the ancient Israelite restitution codes of Exod 22:1&ndash;15 and Lev 6:1&ndash;7: property obtained through theft or fraud had to be returned, often with a penalty multiple. The phrase &ldquo;according to his wealth, the restitution will be&rdquo; suggests the proportional principle of ancient restitution law: the greater the fraud, the greater the repayment. Zophar casts divine retribution in precise legal-economic terms: the wicked man must labor as if to produce wealth but is forbidden from consuming what he produces.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The double indictment &mdash; &ldquo;oppressed and abandoned the poor&rdquo; and &ldquo;seized a house he did not build&rdquo; &mdash; names specific crimes that appear in the OT prophetic indictment literature. Oppression of the poor (<em>&rsquo;āšaq</em>) and violent seizure of property are precisely the charges leveled by Amos (2:6&ndash;8; 5:11&ndash;12), Isaiah (5:8: &ldquo;Woe to you who join house to house&rdquo;), and Micah (2:1&ndash;2). The &ldquo;house he did not build&rdquo; violates the principle of justice by which Deut 20:5 gives a builder the right to inhabit his own house. These are recognizable social crimes, not abstract moral failures.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;He will not feel peace within&rdquo; (<em>lō&rsquo; yēda&rsquo; šalwāh bᵉbiṭnô</em>) introduces the psychological dimension of retributive punishment: the wicked man&rsquo;s inner life will be characterized by the absence of <em>šalwāh</em> (ease, tranquility), the very condition that Job noted the wicked enjoying in 21:23. In ANE thought, <em>šalōm</em> (peace, wholeness) was understood as the proper condition of a person in right relationship with the divine; its absence was both a consequence and a sign of divine disfavor. Zophar claims that the wicked man&rsquo;s possession of things brings him no inner rest.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The consumption of &ldquo;nothing left&rdquo; describes the end of the household line: no food, no heirs, no property to inherit. In ancient Israel, the continuation of a man&rsquo;s name through his household and descendants was the primary form of &ldquo;afterlife&rdquo; &mdash; one lived on through one&rsquo;s children and their memory of the father. The complete consumption of the wicked man&rsquo;s resources means not just personal poverty but the erasure of his name and household from the earth, which was the most comprehensive form of divine punishment short of immediate death.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&ldquo;In the very fullness of his plenty he will be in distress&rdquo; expresses the paradox of abundance-without-security. In ancient Near Eastern royal propaganda, abundance was the primary evidence of divine favor and the king&rsquo;s just rule. The image of &ldquo;the hands of the wretched&rdquo; coming against the wicked man in the moment of his greatest wealth reverses the patron-client structure: those who should be his dependents become his plunderers. The &ldquo;fullness&rdquo; that triggers the attack is the same fullness that the Deuteronomic curses warned about (Deut 32:15: &ldquo;Jeshurun grew fat and kicked&rdquo;).</p>",
    "23": "<p>The divine hurling of fierce wrath (&ldquo;rain it down on him as he eats&rdquo;) uses the storm-god imagery of YHWH as divine warrior. In Mesopotamian mythology, the storm-god Adad hurled fire, hail, and flood against enemies; in Ugaritic mythology, Baal&rsquo;s weapons were lightning bolts. The specific timing &mdash; the attack comes as the wicked man is set to fill his belly &mdash; reflects the ancient pattern of divine irony: judgment falls at the moment of peak presumption. Cf. Belshazzar in Dan 5:1&ndash;6: the divine hand writes on the wall during the feast.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The sequence of divine weapons &mdash; iron weapon avoided, bronze bow striking &mdash; reflects the military technology of the transition from the Bronze Age to the Iron Age (ca. 1200&ndash;1000 BCE). Bronze weapons were the primary military material through most of the biblical period; iron was adopted gradually and was associated with power and invincibility (Deut 33:25; Isa 48:4). The flight from the iron weapon only to be struck by the bronze bow suggests the inescapability of divine judgment: even superior avoidance technology cannot outrun the divine archer.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The anatomical precision of the description &mdash; arrow drawn, passing through the body, shining blade out through the gall, terrors overwhelming &mdash; reflects ancient battlefield experience and medical knowledge. The &ldquo;gall&rdquo; (<em>marrāh</em>) or gall bladder was understood in ancient medicine as a vital organ whose rupture was fatal; arrows that penetrated deeply enough to exit through the abdominal cavity were invariably mortal wounds. The &ldquo;terrors&rdquo; (<em>&rsquo;ēmîm</em>) that &ldquo;overwhelm him&rdquo; are a regular feature of the divine-warrior combat scene, representing the supernatural fear that divine presence brings to its enemies.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;A fire not fanned by wind shall consume him&rdquo; describes a spontaneous divine fire that requires no natural cause. Throughout the OT, spontaneous fire is a primary theophanic element: the burning bush (Exod 3:2), the fire from heaven at Elijah&rsquo;s altar (1 Kgs 18:38), and the fire that destroyed Sodom (Gen 19:24). In ch1:16 the adversary&rsquo;s attack involved &ldquo;fire from God&rdquo; burning Job&rsquo;s sheep. The &ldquo;darkness stored up in his treasures&rdquo; is the retributive inversion of the treasure-imagery: instead of accumulated wealth, the wicked man&rsquo;s storehouse contains divine darkness &mdash; a form of stored judgment awaiting release.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&ldquo;The heavens will expose his guilt, and the earth will rise up against him&rdquo; invokes the ancient cosmological court model in which the created order functions as a witness. The classic ANE treaty form placed the divine witnesses at the top, followed by heaven and earth as the cosmic witnesses who would enforce treaty curses. This treaty-witness formula appears in Moses&rsquo; song (Deut 32:1: &ldquo;Give ear, O heavens, and I will speak; hear, O earth, the words of my mouth&rdquo;) and in the prophetic rîb-pattern (Isa 1:2; Mic 6:1&ndash;2). Zophar claims that the entire created order &mdash; not merely human witnesses &mdash; testifies against the wicked.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&ldquo;The day of his anger&rdquo; (<em>yôm &rsquo;appô</em>) is the individual counterpart to the prophetic &ldquo;Day of the LORD&rdquo; (<em>yôm YHWH</em>) that will bring universal judgment. In Zophar&rsquo;s theology, each wicked person has their personal &ldquo;day of anger&rdquo; when accumulated divine wrath is released and possessions &ldquo;pour away.&rdquo; This individualized retribution theology is consistent with the deuteronomistic principle that divine blessing and curse operate within the lifetime of the individual (Deut 28&ndash;29). The flood imagery (&ldquo;pour away&rdquo;) connects to the ancient judgment-flood archetype.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&ldquo;This is the portion of the wicked man from God&rdquo; is Zophar&rsquo;s formal conclusion, stating the retribution principle as an irrefutable divine decree. The word <em>ḥēleq</em> (portion, share) was used in the distribution of inheritance, priestly portions, and conquered land (cf. the tribal allotments in Joshua); it carried the force of a divinely-determined lot. By using this term, Zophar claims that the wicked man&rsquo;s suffering is not accidental but is his divinely apportioned inheritance &mdash; the precise counterpart to the righteous man&rsquo;s inheritance of blessing. Job&rsquo;s counter-argument in ch21 will demonstrate empirically that this apportionment is not reliably observed.</p>"
  },
  "21": {
    "1": "<p>The speech-attribution formula marks Job&rsquo;s response as the climactic counter-argument of the third cycle. By this point in the dialogue, the three friends have made their most complete statements of retribution theology (Eliphaz in ch15, Bildad in ch18, Zophar in ch20), and Job now delivers his most systematic empirical challenge. The placement of this speech as the final major response before the Elihu interlude and the divine speeches gives it particular structural weight: it is the strongest human theodicy challenge before YHWH himself responds from the whirlwind.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&ldquo;Listen carefully to what I say&rdquo; is the formal attention-call of the wisdom instruction genre. Hebrew wisdom literature regularly opens with the teacher calling students to attention (Prov 1:8; 4:1; 5:1; 22:17: &ldquo;Incline your ear and hear the words of the wise&rdquo;). Job uses the genre conventions of wisdom teaching not to impart traditional instruction but to deliver an argument that overturns it &mdash; a deliberate inversion of the genre&rsquo;s authority structure. The phrase &ldquo;let this be your consolation&rdquo; (<em>wᵉhî nᵉḥāmātkem</em>) is bitterly ironic: Job offers his words as the only real comfort they can provide him, since their theology-based comfort has failed.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;Bear with me so I may speak; after I have spoken, mock away&rdquo; reflects the formal discourse ethics of ancient debate. In ANE court and wisdom contexts, the right of the accused or petitioner to speak without interruption before the judges decided was a recognized procedural right. Job&rsquo;s grant of permission to mock after he speaks is a rhetorical preemption: he acknowledges the friends&rsquo; likely response while asserting that it can only come after his evidence has been presented. The concession &ldquo;mock away&rdquo; (<em>lᵉ&rsquo;û</em>) reveals Job&rsquo;s confidence that the evidence will speak for itself.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;Is my complaint directed to man?&rdquo; establishes the court jurisdiction for Job&rsquo;s argument. In ancient Near Eastern legal systems, different courts had different jurisdictions: disputes between individuals were handled by local elders; cases involving the king were a royal court matter; cases involving the divine realm required a different forum entirely. Job&rsquo;s complaint, he insists, is not a human-court matter but a divine-court case &mdash; which explains why conventional human retributive justice logic doesn&rsquo;t apply. The implication is that the friends are applying the wrong court&rsquo;s rules to a case that belongs before the divine tribunal.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The call to &ldquo;look at me and be appalled&rdquo; followed by &ldquo;lay your hand over your mouth&rdquo; reflects two distinct ancient conventions. &ldquo;Being appalled&rdquo; (<em>šāmam</em>) is the response to a sight that overwhelms comprehension &mdash; the desolation response (Lam 1:16; Isa 52:14: &ldquo;his appearance was so disfigured beyond that of any human being&rdquo;). The hand over the mouth is the ANE gesture of awed, stunned silence before something inexplicable or overwhelming; the same gesture Job makes in 40:4 when he encounters YHWH&rsquo;s speech. Job is demanding that the friends abandon argument and confront the raw theological problem his condition poses.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The physical shuddering that seizes Job when he thinks about the prosperity of the wicked (&ldquo;trembling seizes my flesh&rdquo;) is the somatic response to encountering a terrifying truth. In ANE religious experience, the trembling response (<em>ḥārad</em>) was often associated with the encounter with the holy or with cosmic disorder &mdash; the boundary between divine power and human comprehension. Isa 66:2 describes the one who &ldquo;trembles at my word&rdquo; as the person God honors. Job&rsquo;s trembling is not fear of punishment but the visceral recognition that the reality he is about to describe is genuinely disturbing to moral order.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;Why do the wicked go on living, grow old, and even grow mighty in power?&rdquo; is the classic formulation of the theodicy problem from the perspective of the sufferer. This question has exact parallels in Jer 12:1 (&ldquo;Why does the way of the wicked prosper? Why do all the faithless live at ease?&rdquo;) and Ps 73:3&ndash;12 (the psalmist&rsquo;s envy of the arrogant whose bodies are &ldquo;healthy and strong&rdquo;). In the ancient Near Eastern wisdom tradition, the <em>Babylonian Theodicy</em> poses the same question with no satisfactory resolution. Job&rsquo;s statement is not unique in the OT &mdash; but his insistence on the empirical evidence without retreat into pious qualification marks it as the sharpest formulation of the problem.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The prosperity of the wicked&rsquo;s household &mdash; &ldquo;their children established around them&rdquo; &mdash; describes exactly what Job has lost. Job had ten children (1:2) who were &ldquo;established&rdquo; (<em>kûn</em>) in a regular feast cycle before him; now all are dead and his household is desolate. The wicked man&rsquo;s children and offspring before his eyes are the precise opposite of Job&rsquo;s situation. This deliberate echoing of Job&rsquo;s own family arrangements creates a pointed irony: the man who suffered the retributive removal of his household observes the prosperous persistence of the wicked man&rsquo;s household intact.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;Their houses are safe from fear; the rod of God is not upon them&rdquo; directly refutes Eliphaz&rsquo;s claim in 5:17 that the man God corrects is blessed, and Bildad&rsquo;s implication in 18:7&ndash;21 that the wicked always suffer. The &ldquo;rod&rdquo; (<em>šēbeṭ</em>) of God is the instrument of divine discipline applied to the righteous for their correction (Prov 13:24; Heb 12:6: &ldquo;the Lord disciplines those he loves&rdquo;). Job&rsquo;s observation that the wicked are untouched by this rod inverts the friends&rsquo; assumption: they have argued that suffering = God&rsquo;s rod on the wicked; Job demonstrates that the wicked often experience no such rod.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Agricultural fertility imagery &mdash; the bull breeding without fail, the cow calving without miscarriage &mdash; uses the ANE sign-language of divine blessing. Throughout the ancient Near East, agricultural and pastoral fertility was understood as the direct result of divine favor (cf. Deut 28:4: &ldquo;blessed shall be the offspring of your livestock, the calves of your herds and the lambs of your flocks&rdquo;). The specific detail of the cow not miscarrying (<em>lō&rsquo; tᵉšakkēl</em>) represents the absence of misfortune in the most significant moment of the agricultural economy. The wicked man&rsquo;s livestock reproduces with the same reliability that Deut 28 promises to the faithful covenant-keeper.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The image of the wicked&rsquo;s children running out like a flock and dancing together describes the most socially visible form of prosperity in the ancient world. Children playing publicly signaled a secure and blessed household &mdash; in contrast to the silent streets of a besieged or plague-struck city (Lam 2:19; 5:14: children have ceased their play). Zechariah&rsquo;s eschatological vision of restoration includes boys and girls playing in the streets (Zech 8:5) as a sign of divine blessing. The wicked man&rsquo;s household displays precisely this sign of divine favor &mdash; with no apparent basis in moral desert.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The musical instruments &mdash; timbrel (<em>tōf</em>), harp (<em>kinnôr</em>), flute (<em>&#x27;ûḡāb</em>) &mdash; were the primary instruments of ANE celebration and worship. The timbrel was the instrument of Miriam&rsquo;s song at the Red Sea (Exod 15:20) and of the women who greeted returning warriors (1 Sam 18:6). The harp was the instrument of the Levitical singers in the Jerusalem temple. The flute was associated with feasting and joy (Isa 5:12; 30:29). The wicked man&rsquo;s household employs all three instruments of covenantal celebration &mdash; as if they were themselves the recipients of divine deliverance and blessing.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;They spend their days in prosperity and go down to Sheol in an instant&rdquo; describes the most desirable form of death in ancient Israelite thought: a peaceful death without extended suffering, at the end of a full life. This was understood as a special divine gift (Gen 25:8: Abraham &ldquo;breathed his last and died in a good old age, an old man and full of years&rdquo;; Gen 35:29 of Isaac). The contrast with the wicked&rsquo;s ideal death is devastating to the retribution theology: they achieve what the OT describes as a sign of divine favor. Job&rsquo;s cruel irony is that the wicked&rsquo;s easy death into Sheol is precisely what he himself had wished for (3:17&ndash;22) and been denied.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The direct speech of the wicked &mdash; &ldquo;leave us alone; we have no desire to know your ways&rdquo; &mdash; is a deliberate quotation of the anti-wisdom and anti-covenant position. This reflects the &ldquo;practical atheism&rdquo; that Ps 14:1 describes: the fool who says in his heart &ldquo;there is no God&rdquo; is not making an intellectual claim but practicing a life without reference to divine moral order. The word &ldquo;desire&rdquo; (<em>ḥāpēṣ</em>) is the word used for God&rsquo;s own delight/desire (Ps 37:23; Isa 53:10); the wicked man&rsquo;s declaration that he has no <em>ḥēpeṣ</em> in God&rsquo;s ways is the direct inversion of the covenant relationship.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;Who is the Almighty (<em>Šaddāy</em>) that we should serve him? What do we gain by praying to him?&rdquo; frames religion as an investment calculation &mdash; the same calculus the adversary used in 1:9&ndash;10 (&ldquo;does Job fear God for nothing? Does Job not fear you because you have blessed him?&rdquo;). The wicked man&rsquo;s explicit rejection of the transactional logic inverts the adversary&rsquo;s hypothesis: the adversary claimed that humans only worship God for profit; the wicked man proves the adversary&rsquo;s point by refusing to worship precisely because they calculate no profit in it. This is the theology of Mal 3:14&ndash;15 which Job anticipates by four centuries.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Job&rsquo;s parenthetical caveat &mdash; &ldquo;their prosperity is not in their own hand; the counsel of the wicked I keep far from me&rdquo; &mdash; is a crucial qualification. He is not endorsing the wicked&rsquo;s self-congratulation (their prosperity came from somewhere other than their own competence) nor is he joining their worldview. The theological point is subtle: Job acknowledges that even the wicked&rsquo;s prosperity comes from somewhere beyond their own ability, which actually strengthens his argument &mdash; if their wealth is divinely given, it cannot be evidence of their virtue.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The series of rhetorical questions &mdash; &ldquo;How often is the lamp of the wicked extinguished?&rdquo; &mdash; takes the retribution theology&rsquo;s own poetic images and demands statistical justification. The &ldquo;lamp of the wicked&rdquo; being extinguished appears as a retribution promise in Prov 13:9 and 20:20 (and Bildad uses it in Job 18:6). Job does not deny that the lamp is sometimes extinguished but demands honesty about frequency: the empirical record shows that the wicked often keep their lamps burning to old age. The demand for statistical honesty is a distinctively modern-sounding move, but it reflects the ancient wisdom tradition&rsquo;s empirical observation of human life.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Zophar had used the &ldquo;straw before the wind&rdquo; and &ldquo;chaff swept away by the tempest&rdquo; imagery implicitly (20:8&ndash;9); Job now quotes the retribution theology&rsquo;s favorite agricultural metaphors and again demands frequency data. The threshing-floor imagery &mdash; chaff blown away while grain remains &mdash; was one of the most common ANE metaphors for divine judgment separating the righteous from the wicked (Ps 1:4; Isa 41:15&ndash;16). Job does not deny the metaphor&rsquo;s validity in principle but insists that the metaphor is far less reliably realized than the friends claim.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;You say God stores up punishment for his children&rdquo; reflects an actual theological position that existed in ANE thought and OT tradition: Exod 20:5 (&ldquo;visiting the iniquity of the fathers on the children to the third and fourth generation&rdquo;). Job has heard this as the friends&rsquo; implicit response to his observation that the wicked prosper: they will argue that the punishment falls on the next generation. Job&rsquo;s counter &mdash; &ldquo;let him repay the man himself and let him know it&rdquo; &mdash; demands individual accountability, which anticipates the theological development of Jer 31:29&ndash;30 and Ezek 18:1&ndash;4 (each person dies for their own sin).</p>",
    "20": "<p>The cup of divine wrath &mdash; &ldquo;let him drink of the wrath of the Almighty&rdquo; &mdash; is a distinctively prophetic image for the concentrated experience of divine judgment. The wrath-cup appears in Ps 75:8 (&ldquo;in the hand of YHWH is a cup of foaming wine&rdquo;), Isa 51:17,22 (the cup of wrath and staggering), and Jer 25:15&ndash;17 (the cup of wrath drunk by all nations). In the NT, this cup language appears in the Gethsemane prayers (Matt 26:39,42) and in Rev 14:10; 16:19. Job&rsquo;s use of the wrath-cup image demands that the wicked man experience personally what the cup of retribution would mean &mdash; rather than having it deferred to his descendants.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;For what pleasure does he take in his house after him, when the number of his months is severed?&rdquo; is a logical argument about posthumous punishment. In ancient Israelite thought, the dead in Sheol were effectively beyond further divine action (Ps 88:10&ndash;12: &ldquo;Will you do wonders for the dead? Do the dead rise up to praise you?&rdquo;). If punishment falls only after death, the person who suffered is no longer capable of experiencing it &mdash; making the punishment experientially irrelevant to the individual. Job thus demands that divine justice operate within the lifetime of the guilty party, not deferred to a state where it cannot be experienced.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&ldquo;Will anyone teach God knowledge?&rdquo; is Job&rsquo;s ironic concession to divine transcendence &mdash; but used here in the context of theodicy rather than doxology. The rhetorical question resembles Isa 40:13&ndash;14 (&ldquo;Who has directed the Spirit of YHWH, or as his counselor has taught him?&rdquo;) and Rom 11:34, but Job&rsquo;s point is different: if God judges &ldquo;those on high&rdquo; (possibly the heavenly beings or the exalted nations), then the distribution of suffering in the human world should reflect that justice &mdash; and Job&rsquo;s empirical observations suggest it does not, consistently.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;One person dies in full vigor, completely at ease and secure&rdquo; describes the blessed death recognized throughout ANE culture as a sign of divine favor: to die full, prosperous, and at ease is the positive eschatology of the OT without resurrection hope. The patriarchal deaths &mdash; Abraham &ldquo;in a good old age, an old man and full of years&rdquo; (Gen 25:8), Isaac (Gen 35:29), David dying &ldquo;in a good old age, full of days, riches, and honor&rdquo; (1 Chr 29:28) &mdash; all use this language. Job now applies this same privileged-death language to a person whose moral status is unspecified, breaking the assumption that such a death indicates righteousness.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&ldquo;His sides full of milk and his bones saturated with marrow&rdquo; are the ANE medical indicators of ideal physical health. Fat and marrow were the richest and most nutritionally valuable components of the ancient diet; they were offered in the most significant sacrifices (Lev 3:3&ndash;4; Ps 63:5: &ldquo;my soul will be satisfied as with fat and rich food&rdquo;). &ldquo;Sides full of milk&rdquo; (<em>&rsquo;ăṭînāw māle&rsquo; ḥālāb</em>) is a unique expression probably indicating the full, well-nourished flanks of a prosperous person; marrow saturation represents internal richness at the most fundamental anatomical level.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&ldquo;Another dies in bitterness of soul, having never tasted what is good&rdquo; directly contrasts with v23&ndash;24. The phrase &ldquo;never tasted what is good&rdquo; (<em>lō&rsquo; &rsquo;ākal bᵃṭṭôbāh</em>) is the exact language of Eccl 6:2&ndash;3 (&ldquo;a man to whom God gives wealth, property, and honor&hellip; but God does not give him the ability to enjoy them&rdquo;). The parallel between Job 21 and Ecclesiastes on this point is one of the closest thematic connections in the wisdom literature: both books observe the complete disconnection between moral quality and quality of experience, refusing to resolve it with easy theological formulas.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;They lie down together in the dust, and worms cover them both&rdquo; is the great leveling image of death. The dust (<em>&rsquo;āpār</em>) that both the prosperous and the bitter man return to echoes the creation narrative of Gen 2:7 and 3:19; the reversal of the breath of life into dust is the common fate of all humanity. Worms covering them both is the ultimate physical equalizer &mdash; the same biological process regardless of moral status or quality of life. Eccl 9:2 states the same principle: &ldquo;the same fate overtakes the righteous and the wicked.&rdquo; Job uses this biological fact as a theodicy argument: if death equalizes, then the quality of dying cannot be the primary evidence of divine judgment.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&ldquo;I know your thoughts and the schemes you wrongfully contrive against me&rdquo; shifts the frame from Job&rsquo;s theodicy argument to the personal dynamic with the friends. The word &ldquo;schemes&rdquo; (<em>mazimmôt</em>) appears in both positive and negative senses in Proverbs (Prov 1:4 uses it for wise planning; Prov 12:2 for the wicked man&rsquo;s schemes). Job accuses the friends of deliberately constructing false arguments against him &mdash; not merely being wrong but being wrongfully intentional in their wrongness. This prepares for his devastating final verdict in v34.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&ldquo;Where is the house of the noble man? Where are the dwelling places of the wicked?&rdquo; quotes the implied question of the friends&rsquo; argument: they have claimed that the wicked&rsquo;s houses are always destroyed (Bildad in 18:14&ndash;21 described the wicked man&rsquo;s tent being destroyed and his dwelling place gone). Job anticipates their rhetorical question and turns it into an invitation to travel and see empirically. The ANE honor-shame system recognized the household as the visible external sign of divine favor or disfavor; Job challenges the friends to actually observe what the world&rsquo;s households look like.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&ldquo;Have you not asked those who travel the roads?&rdquo; is an appeal to the ancient practice of gathering wisdom from travelers. In a world without newspapers or systematic data collection, travelers who passed through many regions were the primary sources of information about conditions across the world. Wisdom literature valued this empirical observation (Prov 25:25: &ldquo;like cold water to a weary soul is good news from a distant land&rdquo;). The appeal to travelers&rsquo; testimony is an appeal to universal human experience beyond the narrow social circle of the friends and their received tradition &mdash; empirical counter-evidence from the broader world.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&ldquo;That the wicked is spared on the day of disaster and delivered through to the day of wrath&rdquo; is the travelers&rsquo; reported testimony &mdash; the empirical observation that Job claims universal human experience confirms. The &ldquo;day of disaster&rdquo; (<em>yôm &rsquo;êd</em>) and &ldquo;day of wrath&rdquo; (<em>yôm &rsquo;ebrôt</em>) are the very occasions when retribution theology says the wicked should fall. Job&rsquo;s claim is that travelers universally report the opposite pattern: the wicked are &ldquo;reserved&rdquo; (<em>yûbal</em>) for the day of disaster &mdash; meaning they are kept safe through it and delivered past it, not struck by it.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&ldquo;Who will tell him to his face what he has done? Who will repay him for his deeds?&rdquo; identifies the social problem with the wicked man&rsquo;s prosperity: the absence of accountability. In ancient Near Eastern societies, formal accountability operated through public shaming, legal proceedings before elders at the gate, and the threat of divine retribution. But for the truly powerful wicked man, none of these mechanisms functions: no one dares confront him directly, and divine punishment fails to materialize. The question is left deliberately unanswered &mdash; it is the unresolved problem at the heart of Job&rsquo;s theodicy challenge.</p>",
    "32": "<p>&ldquo;He is borne to the grave, and a vigil is kept over his tomb&rdquo; describes an honored burial &mdash; the opposite of the shameful end Bildad predicted for the wicked in 18:17&ndash;20 (&ldquo;his memory perishes from the earth&rdquo;). In ancient Israel, proper burial was a theological and social necessity (cf. the Deuteronomic curses for those left unburied; the honor given to patriarchs in burial caves). A state funeral with a mourning watch over the tomb was the ultimate social recognition of a person&rsquo;s standing. Job observes that the wicked frequently receive precisely this &mdash; honored burial, community tribute, lasting memorial.</p>",
    "33": "<p>&ldquo;The clods of the valley lie sweetly upon him&rdquo; is a poetic image of gentle burial and rest in death. The &ldquo;valley&rdquo; (<em>gêy</em>) as the location of burial evokes the valley as the liminal space between the living (on the heights) and the dead (below); the soft clods of valley soil resting gently on the deceased describe an easy return to earth. The vast procession following him and the numberless dead who preceded him places the wicked man within the great company of all who have died &mdash; undifferentiated in death from the righteous. The peaceful burial scene is the final empirical evidence against the retribution theology.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Job&rsquo;s final verdict &mdash; &ldquo;How then do you comfort me with empty words, when nothing but falsehood remains in your answers?&rdquo; &mdash; is his most devastating assessment of the friends&rsquo; entire theological enterprise. The word &ldquo;falsehood&rdquo; (<em>māʿal</em>) is the vocabulary of treacherous unfaithfulness used in legal and covenant contexts (Lev 5:15; Num 5:12). By applying this word to the friends&rsquo; answers, Job is not merely saying they are mistaken but that their arguments are a form of covenant betrayal &mdash; using God&rsquo;s name in support of false testimony. This verdict is confirmed by YHWH in 42:7&ndash;8: &ldquo;you have not spoken of me what is right, as my servant Job has.&rdquo;</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'job')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'job', c)
    total = sum(len(vs) for vs in CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'job mkt-context: {total} entries written (ch19-21)')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
